Note:
RUNTIME MATH WRAPPER

This file is the runtime-facing transcendental math surface. It exposes
the C-runtime ABI symbols that the previous C runtime exported
(runtime_sin, runtime_cos) and adds the full complementary surface that
any caller of Runa will reasonably expect from the runtime: the rest of
the trigonometric family, the inverse trigonometric family, radian-mode
counterparts, and angle conversions.

All float values cross this boundary as Integer bit-patterns of an
IEEE-754 binary64 value. The Runa convention is that every float
parameter and return is its raw 64-bit pattern reinterpreted as an
Integer; the caller is responsible for the bit-cast at the language
boundary.

Implementation sources:
  - All transcendental work is delegated to compiler/frontend/primitives/
    core/trig_core.runa which implements:
      - Cody-Waite range reduction modulo 2*pi
      - 8-term Horner-form Taylor series for sin and cos on a half-cycle
      - Half-range symmetry to keep the Taylor input small
      - 13-term atan Taylor series with denominator precomputation
      - 10-term asin Taylor series with half-angle identity for |x| > 0.5
      - Quadrant-aware atan2 dispatch
  - This file is a name-stable export layer; the trig_core implementation
    can evolve independently (range reduction, term count, hardware
    intrinsics) without ABI churn for callers.

Why a wrapper file at all:
  - trig_core's natural names (sin_degrees, cos_degrees) follow the
    primitive naming convention. The C runtime exported runtime_sin and
    runtime_cos. Stage1 binaries linked against the old runtime expect
    those symbol names. Renaming the primitives would touch every caller
    in the compiler tree.
  - Keeping the wrapper here means the primitive layer stays focused on
    math and the integration layer owns ABI compatibility.

Symbol naming convention:
  - runtime_sin / runtime_cos take degrees (matches old C runtime ABI)
  - sin_rad / cos_rad / tan_rad take radians
  - sin_deg / cos_deg / tan_deg take degrees
  - asin_rad / acos_rad / atan_rad return radians
  - asin_deg / acos_deg / atan_deg return degrees
  - atan2_rad / atan2_deg take (y, x) and return the corresponding angle
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/trig_core.runa" as Trig

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 1 - C-RUNTIME-COMPATIBLE ABI EXPORTS
============================================================================
These two functions match the signatures from the legacy runtime.c so
that stage1 binaries which still reference runtime_sin / runtime_cos
link cleanly against the new Runa runtime.

Both take an Integer bit-pattern representing a float64 angle in degrees
and return the corresponding sine or cosine as an Integer bit-pattern.
:End Note

Process called "runtime_sin" takes degrees_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.sin_degrees(degrees_bits)
End Process

Process called "runtime_cos" takes degrees_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.cos_degrees(degrees_bits)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 2 - DEGREE-BASED TRIGONOMETRY
============================================================================
Pleasant aliases for callers that prefer the shorter spelling. Every
function in this section takes an Integer bit-pattern in degrees.
:End Note

Process called "sin_deg" takes degrees_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.sin_degrees(degrees_bits)
End Process

Process called "cos_deg" takes degrees_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.cos_degrees(degrees_bits)
End Process

Process called "tan_deg" takes degrees_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.tan_degrees(degrees_bits)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 3 - RADIAN-BASED TRIGONOMETRY
============================================================================
For callers that already hold an angle in radians. Argument reduction
(modulo 2*pi via Cody-Waite) happens inside trig_core; callers do not
need to pre-reduce.
:End Note

Process called "sin_rad" takes radians_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.sin_radians(radians_bits)
End Process

Process called "cos_rad" takes radians_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.cos_radians(radians_bits)
End Process

Process called "tan_rad" takes radians_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.tan_radians(radians_bits)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 4 - INVERSE TRIGONOMETRY (RETURNS RADIANS)
============================================================================
Domain notes:
  - asin and acos require -1 <= x <= 1
  - atan accepts all finite inputs
  - atan2 accepts all finite (y, x) and dispatches by quadrant
:End Note

Process called "asin_rad" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.asin(x_bits)
End Process

Process called "acos_rad" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.acos(x_bits)
End Process

Process called "atan_rad" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.atan(x_bits)
End Process

Process called "atan2_rad" takes y_bits as Integer, x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.atan2(y_bits, x_bits)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 5 - INVERSE TRIGONOMETRY (RETURNS DEGREES)
============================================================================
Convenience layer for callers that prefer degree output. The radian
result is converted by trig_core.radians_to_degrees, which uses the
exact 180/pi constant stored in trig_core.deg_per_rad.
:End Note

Process called "asin_deg" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.radians_to_degrees(Trig.asin(x_bits))
End Process

Process called "acos_deg" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.radians_to_degrees(Trig.acos(x_bits))
End Process

Process called "atan_deg" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.radians_to_degrees(Trig.atan(x_bits))
End Process

Process called "atan2_deg" takes y_bits as Integer, x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.radians_to_degrees(Trig.atan2(y_bits, x_bits))
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 6 - ANGLE CONVERSIONS
============================================================================
Direct unit conversions. These are pure multiplications by a constant;
the actual constants (pi/180 and 180/pi) are precomputed in trig_core
as bit patterns for reuse.
:End Note

Process called "deg_to_rad" takes degrees_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.degrees_to_radians(degrees_bits)
End Process

Process called "rad_to_deg" takes radians_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.radians_to_degrees(radians_bits)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 7 - REDUCED-RANGE PRIMITIVES (POWER USERS)
============================================================================
Exposed for code that has already performed its own argument reduction
and needs to skip the modulo-2*pi step inside sin_radians / cos_radians.
The input MUST satisfy 0 <= x <= 2*pi. Behavior is undefined outside
that range; callers are expected to know what they are doing.

These are useful for batch loops where many sines or cosines are
evaluated on values produced by an incremental angle generator (e.g.,
FFT inner loops, oscillator banks) and the caller can guarantee the
input is already reduced.
:End Note

Process called "sin_rad_reduced" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.sin_radians_reduced(x_bits)
End Process

Process called "cos_rad_reduced" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Trig.cos_radians_reduced(x_bits)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 8 - CONSTANTS
============================================================================
Common float64 constants exposed as Integer bit-patterns. These avoid
forcing the caller to re-derive them and guarantee bit-identity with
the values used inside trig_core's argument reduction.
:End Note

Process called "math_pi" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.pi()
End Process

Process called "math_two_pi" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.two_pi()
End Process

Process called "math_half_pi" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.half_pi()
End Process

Process called "math_quarter_pi" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.quarter_pi()
End Process

Process called "math_pi_over_180" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.pi_over_180()
End Process

Process called "math_deg_per_rad" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.deg_per_rad()
End Process

Process called "math_e" returns Integer:
    Return Trig.float_e()
End Process
